## Tech Stack

DeFi Panda is built with a modern blockchain analytics stack optimized for indexing and serving DeFi vault data:

### Core Framework
- **Ponder (v0.11.20)** - Blockchain indexing framework for building real-time analytics applications
- **Node.js (>=22.14)** - Runtime environment
- **TypeScript (v5.8.3)** - Primary language for type safety and developer experience

### API & Web Framework
- **Hono (v4.8.3)** - Fast, lightweight web framework for building REST APIs
- **Viem (v2.31.4)** - TypeScript interface for Ethereum, providing type-safe blockchain interactions

### Data & Validation
- **Zod (v4.0.5)** - Schema validation library for runtime type checking and API validation
- **date-fns (v4.1.0)** - Modern date utility library for time-based calculations and formatting

### Utilities
- **Remeda (v2.25.0)** - Functional programming utility library (lodash alternative) for data transformations

### Development & Testing
- **Vitest (v3.2.4)** - Fast unit testing framework with TypeScript support
- **ESLint (v9.29.0)** - Code linting with Ponder-specific configuration
- **eslint-config-ponder (v0.11.20)** - Ponder framework ESLint rules and best practices

### Development Guidelines
- Use **TypeScript** for all source code with strict type checking
- Leverage **Ponder** conventions for blockchain event indexing and database schema
- Use **Hono** for REST API endpoints with proper error handling
- Implement **Zod** schemas for all API inputs/outputs and data validation
- Use **Viem** for all Ethereum interactions (no ethers.js or web3.js)
- Apply **Remeda** for functional data transformations over imperative loops
- Write tests with **Vitest** focusing on business logic and API endpoints
- Follow **date-fns** patterns for all date/time operations

### Architecture Patterns
- Event-driven architecture for blockchain data indexing
- RESTful API design with proper HTTP status codes
- Functional programming patterns for data processing
- Type-safe database operations through Ponder's ORM
- Immutable data structures where possible

### Maintenance
**⚠️ Important:** Always update this tech stack documentation when:
- Installing new dependencies (`pnpm add <package>`)
- Upgrading existing packages (`pnpm update`)
- Changing Node.js version requirements
- Adding new development tools or frameworks
- Removing deprecated libraries

Keep version numbers current and update guidelines accordingly.